<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="evaluation-benchmarks"><metadata><tier>geek</tier><group>ai</group><domain>ml-ops</domain><summary>Multi-model comparison and continuous production monitoring methodology. Versioned benchmark runs track model performance.</summary><tags><tag>benchmarking</tag><tag>model-comparison</tag><tag>production-monitoring</tag><tag>evaluation</tag><tag>quality-assurance</tag></tags><difficulty>intermediate</difficulty><created>2026-04-26</created></metadata><content><title>Evaluation Benchmarks</title><summary>Multi-model comparison and continuous production monitoring methodology. ModelComparison runs the same test set across multiple LLMs and ranks them per metric. BenchmarkSuite standardizes evaluation across classification, QA, summarization, and code task types. ProductionEvaluator samples live traffic and runs automated quality checks with alerting.</summary><why><p>A single evaluation snapshot reveals current quality but not trends. Versioned benchmark runs track whether model changes improve or degrade performance over time. Production sampling catches regressions before users report them, and multi-model comparison removes guesswork from provider or version selection decisions.</p></why><when-to-use><list><item>Selecting a model or provider for a new project: run ModelComparison across candidate models on a domain-representative test set</item><item>Establishing a repeatable performance baseline before any major prompt or model change</item><item>Setting up continuous production monitoring that detects quality regressions before users report them</item><item>Comparing a fine-tuned model to the base model with consistent methodology</item><item>Building a CI quality gate that blocks deployment if benchmark scores drop below threshold</item></list></when-to-use><when-not-to-use><list><item>The test set has fewer than 100 cases — ModelComparison results will have confidence intervals too wide to be actionable</item><item>The benchmark dataset is derived from the same source as the training data — this produces artificially inflated scores; use a held-out dataset from a different collection</item><item>The goal is evaluating safety or alignment — ProductionEvaluator string checks are insufficient; use red-teaming and dedicated safety benchmarks (e.g., ToxiGen, BBQ)</item><item>A single benchmark run is expected to fully characterize model quality — benchmarks capture what they measure, not everything that matters in production</item></list></when-not-to-use><section name="Limitations and Failure Points"><list><item>ModelComparison._create_comparison_report assumes "higher is better" for all metrics — this is wrong for latency; the ranking direction must be parameterized per metric</item><item>BenchmarkSuite.run_all runs benchmarks sequentially — for large test sets and multiple benchmark types, this is slow; parallelize with asyncio or a thread pool</item><item>ProductionEvaluator._run_checks uses hardcoded error patterns ("sorry, i cannot", "as an ai") — these are model-version-specific and go stale as providers change phrasings</item><item>The production evaluator logs all evaluations in memory — for high-volume systems (&gt;10k req/day), this causes OOM; flush to a database or observability platform every N evaluations</item><item>BenchmarkSuite.load_qa_benchmark only supports a flat JSON format — real datasets (SQuAD, TriviaQA) require format adapters</item><item>ModelComparison creates one ModelEvaluator per model but shares the same cases list — if cases include mutable metadata (dict), side effects can corrupt results across model runs</item></list></section><section name="ModelComparison — Multi-Model Benchmark Runner"><p>ModelComparison class: running identical test sets across multiple models, ranking by metric, latency comparison, and parallelization for large test sets.</p><rules><rule><statement>Run all models at temperature=0 with the identical system prompt and test cases.</statement><rationale>Any difference in prompt or temperature produces incomparable results; the comparison must control everything except the model.</rationale></rule><rule><statement>Use at least 50 cases per task type for ModelComparison; below 50, metric rankings reverse between runs due to sampling variance.</statement><rationale>Statistical reliability requires sufficient sample size; fewer than 50 cases produce confidence intervals too wide for actionable decisions.</rationale></rule><rule><statement>Parallelize model evaluation with asyncio.gather or separate subagents — never run models sequentially for large test sets.</statement><rationale>3 models x 100 cases x 1s latency = 300s sequential; parallelization reduces this to ~100s wall-clock time.</rationale></rule></rules></section><section name="Ranking Inversion Gotcha"><rules><rule><statement>When using ModelComparison rankings for model selection, invert the latency ranking — lower latency is better, but the default ranking sorts higher values first.</statement><rationale>The comparison report assumes "higher is better" for all metrics. Latency ranking must be explicitly inverted or the fastest model is ranked last.</rationale></rule></rules><antipattern><description>Using ModelComparison.rankings["latency_ms"][0] as the "best" model selection.</description><reason>The highest latency model is ranked first by the default sort; the agent selects the slowest model when it intends to pick the fastest.</reason></antipattern></section><section name="Dataset Hygiene"><rules><rule><statement>Maintain a frozen "golden" test set for regression detection and a separate "current" test set that grows with new failure modes from production.</statement><rationale>A growing test set captures new edge cases; a frozen golden set ensures regressions are detectable even as coverage expands.</rationale></rule><rule><statement>Store benchmark datasets in version control (Git LFS or DVC) alongside the prompt versions they were designed to test.</statement><rationale>Changes to either the dataset or the prompt should trigger a benchmark re-run; version co-location makes this dependency explicit.</rationale></rule></rules><antipattern><description>Using the same test set to tune prompts and then to evaluate quality.</description><reason>The test set is no longer an unbiased evaluator once it has been used to optimize — benchmark overfitting produces inflated scores.</reason></antipattern></section><section name="BenchmarkSuite — Standardized Task Evaluation"><p>BenchmarkSuite class for loading and running classification, QA, summarization, and code benchmarks with appropriate metrics per task type.</p><section name="Task-Metric Mapping"><rules><rule><statement>Select metrics appropriate to task type: exact_match for classification, contains_match + BLEU for QA, ROUGE for summarization.</statement><rationale>Applying BLEU to classification or exact_match to generation produces meaningless scores; metric-task mismatch is the most common benchmarking error.</rationale></rule></rules><list><item>classification → exact_match, contains_match</item><item>qa → contains_match, bleu_score</item><item>summarization → rouge_score</item><item>code → pass@1 (execute and check)</item></list></section><section name="Dataset Format Adapters"><rules><rule><statement>Validate that loaded cases share a consistent schema before running benchmarks — check that expected_output is not None for more than 5% of cases.</statement><rationale>BenchmarkSuite does not validate loaded case schemas; mixing datasets with different field names silently produces empty expected_output and misleadingly high metrics.</rationale></rule><rule><statement>Write a format adapter for each external dataset (SQuAD, TriviaQA, MMLU) that maps its schema to EvaluationCase(input, expected_output, metadata).</statement><rationale>BenchmarkSuite.load_qa_benchmark only supports a flat JSON format; real benchmark datasets require custom adapters.</rationale></rule></rules></section><section name="Standard External Benchmarks"><p>For production use, prefer established benchmarks over custom datasets for cross-model comparability.</p><list><item>MMLU — multi-task knowledge, accuracy metric, 57 subjects</item><item>HellaSwag — commonsense reasoning, accuracy</item><item>TruthfulQA — factual accuracy, MC1/MC2 metrics</item><item>HumanEval — code generation, pass@1/pass@10</item><item>GSM8K — math reasoning, accuracy</item></list><rules><rule><statement>Use lm-evaluation-harness for running standard benchmarks; do not reimplement MMLU or HellaSwag evaluation logic manually.</statement><rationale>Standard benchmark evaluation has subtle implementation details (few-shot formatting, answer normalization) that manual reimplementation gets wrong, producing non-comparable scores.</rationale></rule></rules></section></section><section name="ProductionEvaluator — Continuous Quality Monitoring"><p>Sampled production evaluation with JSONL persistence, sample rate guidance by traffic volume, and alert analysis prompt pattern.</p><section name="Sample Rate Guidance"><rules><rule><statement>Set sample rate by traffic: 10% at 1k req/day, 1% at 100k req/day, 0.1% at 1M req/day — keep evaluation cost below 5% of production inference cost.</statement><rationale>Over-sampling wastes budget without improving signal quality; under-sampling misses infrequent failure modes.</rationale></rule><rule><statement>Persist evaluation records to a JSONL file or time-series database rather than accumulating in memory.</statement><rationale>In-memory accumulation causes OOM in high-volume long-running processes; JSONL files survive process restarts and can be analyzed historically.</rationale></rule></rules></section><section name="Time-Series Analysis"><rules><rule><statement>Track benchmark results as a time-series over 4-8 weeks — a single evaluation snapshot has low diagnostic value; trends reveal model drift and quality degradation.</statement><rationale>Point-in-time scores show current quality but not whether it is improving or declining; trend lines are required for meaningful operational decisions.</rationale></rule><rule><statement>Calibrate error pattern strings (e.g., "sorry, i cannot", "as an ai") against actual model outputs every 3-6 months.</statement><rationale>Provider phrasings change across model versions; stale patterns produce false negatives that mask real quality issues.</rationale></rule></rules><antipattern><description>Running ProductionEvaluator.evaluate_request with random.random() and expecting reproducible debugging of a specific production failure.</description><reason>Non-seeded sampling is not reproducible; the failing request will not reliably be re-captured. Log all raw requests separately from the evaluation sample.</reason></antipattern></section></section><section name="Agentic Workflow"><p>An agent running benchmark evaluation should load a versioned test dataset, run ModelComparison or BenchmarkSuite at temperature=0, compare results to the stored baseline (from previous run or deployment), and return a structured pass/fail report. For production monitoring, a lightweight background subagent samples live requests at 5-10%, applies ProductionEvaluator checks, and pushes aggregated metrics to the observability platform every hour for dashboard display.</p><section name="Recommended Subagents"><list><item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — drives benchmark setup and CI integration from a task card</item><item>A benchmark-runner subagent (custom) — takes model list, test dataset path, metric list; returns ModelComparison report JSON</item><item>A production-monitor subagent (custom) — runs on a cron schedule, queries sampled evaluations from the past hour, compares to baseline, creates alerts or SDD tasks on regression</item></list></section><section name="Prompt Patterns"><p>Model comparison benchmark prompt:</p><code lang="text">Run a model comparison benchmark for the following models: {model_list}.
Test dataset: {N} cases, task type: {classification|qa|summarization}.
Metrics: {metric_list}. Temperature: 0.

Return JSON: {
  "winner": str,
  "rankings": {"metric": [model_list_ranked]},
  "comparison": {"metric": {"model": score}},
  "recommendation": str,
  "latency_ms": {"model": float}
}</code><p>Production metrics analysis prompt:</p><code lang="text">Analyze production evaluation metrics from the past 24h:
- non_empty pass rate: {rate}
- reasonable_length pass rate: {rate}
- no_error_patterns pass rate: {rate}
- avg output length: {chars}

Compare to 7-day baseline. Flag any check that dropped &gt;5% absolute.
Return JSON: {"alerts": [{"check": str, "delta": float, "severity": str}], "overall_health": "ok|degraded|critical"}</code></section></section><section name="CLI Tools"><list><item>lm-evaluation-harness — EleutherAI standard benchmark runner (MMLU, HellaSwag, etc.) — pip install lm-eval / github.com/EleutherAI/lm-evaluation-harness</item><item>openai SDK — Run ModelComparison and BenchmarkSuite API calls — pip install openai</item><item>datasets (HuggingFace) — Load standard benchmark datasets (SQuAD, MMLU, TriviaQA) — pip install datasets</item><item>evaluate (HuggingFace) — Metric implementations for benchmark scoring — pip install evaluate</item><item>pandas — Aggregate and pivot benchmark results — pip install pandas</item><item>pytest — Run benchmark suite as CI test with threshold assertions — pip install pytest</item></list></section><section name="Services and Applications"><list><item>Braintrust (SaaS) — Best for versioned benchmark management and comparison history. SDK + dataset versioning.</item><item>Langfuse (SaaS/OSS) — Attach benchmark scores to traces for trend tracking. Score API per trace.</item><item>OpenAI Evals (OSS) — Standardized benchmark definitions; good for regression CI. YAML/Python eval runner.</item><item>HELM (Stanford CRFM) (OSS) — Gold standard for holistic model comparison; complex setup. Requires local model access.</item><item>PromptFoo (OSS) — Fast multi-model comparison with LLM-as-judge support. YAML config, CI-ready.</item><item>Weights &amp; Biases (SaaS) — Compare benchmark metrics across model versions in W&amp;B tables. Log benchmark runs as W&amp;B runs.</item></list></section><section name="Best Practices"><list><item>Store benchmark datasets in version control (Git LFS or DVC) alongside prompt versions — changes to either should trigger a benchmark re-run to detect regressions</item><item>Always run benchmarks at temperature=0 with a fixed random seed where the API supports it — stochastic results between runs are noise, not signal</item><item>Maintain a "golden" test set that never changes: use it for regression detection. Maintain a separate "current" test set that grows with new failure modes from production</item><item>For ModelComparison, use at least 50 cases per task type — fewer than 50 produces rankings that reverse with each new run due to sampling variance</item><item>Track benchmark results in a time-series database (Langfuse, W&amp;B, or simple JSONL) — a single evaluation snapshot has low value; trends over 4-8 weeks reveal model drift and quality degradation</item><item>For production ProductionEvaluator, set sample rate based on traffic: 10% at 1k req/day, 1% at 100k req/day, 0.1% at 1M req/day — evaluation should cost &lt;5% of production inference cost</item><item>Calibrate error pattern strings against actual model outputs every 3-6 months; provider phrasings change and stale patterns produce false negatives</item></list></section><section name="AI-Agent Gotchas"><list><item>ModelComparison rankings assume higher metric value is better — latency ranking is therefore reversed; agents using ranking output for model selection must explicitly handle latency inversion</item><item>Running ModelComparison with 3 models × 100 cases × 1s latency = 300s sequential — agents should parallelize model evaluation with asyncio.gather or separate subagents, not run serially</item><item>ProductionEvaluator.evaluate_request uses random.random() which is not reproducible — for debugging a specific production failure, the sampling will not reliably re-capture it; always log all raw requests separately from the evaluation sample</item><item>Benchmark overfitting is a real risk: if the same test set is used to tune prompts, the test set is no longer an unbiased evaluator — agents must not expose the full test set to prompt-optimization loops</item><item>The BenchmarkSuite does not validate that loaded cases share a consistent schema — mixing datasets with different field names (e.g., "answer" vs. "label") silently produces empty expected_output fields and misleadingly high metrics</item></list></section><section name="Code Example"><p>Production evaluator with persistent logging to JSONL:</p><code lang="python">import json
import random
import logging
from datetime import datetime
from pathlib import Path

class PersistentProductionEvaluator:
    def __init__(self, log_path: str, sample_rate: float = 0.1):
        self.log_path = Path(log_path)
        self.sample_rate = sample_rate
        self.logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

    def evaluate_request(self, input: str, output: str, metadata: dict = None) -&gt; dict | None:
        if random.random() &gt;= self.sample_rate:
            return None
        checks = {
            "non_empty": len(output.strip()) &gt; 0,
            "reasonable_length": 10 &lt; len(output) &lt; 10000,
            "no_error_patterns": not any(
                p in output.lower() for p in ["sorry, i cannot", "as an ai", "i'm unable"]
            ),
        }
        record = {
            "timestamp": datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),
            "input_length": len(input),
            "output_length": len(output),
            "checks": checks,
            "metadata": metadata or {},
        }
        with self.log_path.open("a") as f:
            f.write(json.dumps(record) + "\n")
        if not all(checks.values()):
            self.logger.warning("Quality check failed: %s", {k: v for k, v in checks.items() if not v})
        return record</code></section><templates><template path="templates/persistent-evaluator.py" purpose="Production evaluator with JSONL log flush instead of in-memory accumulation (~40 lines)" /><template path="templates/benchmark-alert-prompt.txt" purpose="Prompt template for analyzing 24h production metrics vs. 7-day baseline" /></templates><see-also><link href="https://crfm.stanford.edu/helm/">HELM Benchmark</link><link href="https://github.com/EleutherAI/lm-evaluation-harness">LM Evaluation Harness (EleutherAI)</link><link href="https://github.com/openai/evals">OpenAI Evals</link><link href="https://promptfoo.dev/docs/guides/compare-llms/">PromptFoo — Model Comparison</link><link href="https://huggingface.co/docs/datasets/">HuggingFace Datasets</link><link href="https://www.braintrust.dev/docs/guides/evals">Braintrust — Evaluation</link><link href="https://docs.ragas.io/">RAGAS — RAG Benchmarking</link></see-also></content></methodology>